         <abstract>
            <p>The Employee Retirement Income Security Act gives the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation the power to reach employer assets with the priority of a federal tax lien over conventional creditors. It also provides for "contingent liability insurance" that shields employers from the application of this power. How important is it whether the employer bears the full burden of its unfunded pension liability or no burden? In a sample of 40 major employer corporations, the debt-to-equity ratio rises more than 50 per cent when the unfunded vested pension liability is incorporated into the employer's capital structure.</p>
          </abstract>
